, from his early clandestine education as a slave in a noble household to his distinguished career as a schoolmaster at the University of Granada. When intensifying racial discrimination and the chaos of the Morisco Revolt threatened Latino’s hard-won status, he set out to secure his position by publishing an epic poem in Latin verse, the Austrias Carmen, that would demonstrate his mastery of Europe’s international literary language and celebrate his own African heritage.Through Latino’s remarkable, hitherto untold story, Wright illuminates the racial and religious tensions of sixteenth-century Spain and the position of black Africans within Spain’s nascent empire and within the emerging African diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBlacksxHistoryx16th centuryxSpain. 0aBlackszSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aEpic poetry, Latin (Medieval and modern)xHistory and criticism. 0aNaval battles in literature. 0aPoets, BlackxBiographyxSpain. 0aPoets, BlackzSpainvBiography. 0aRace discriminationxHistoryx16th centuryxSpain. 0aRace discriminationzSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aRenaissancexSpain. 0aRenaissancezSpain. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262554940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442625549423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442625549.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles